play of haemodynamic stress and \nneurohormonal activation . Reduced cardiac output or elevated filling pressures \nactivate compensatory mechanisms including the sympathetic nervous system, renin –\nangiotensin –aldosterone system, and arginine vasopressin. While initially adaptive, \nchronic activation leads to myocardi al fibrosis, adverse ventricular remodelling, sodium \nand water retention, endothelial dysfunction, and worsening ventricular performance. \nAt a cellular level, abnormalities in calcium handling, mitochondrial energetics, and \ncardiomyocyte apoptosis further perpetuate contractile dysfunction, creating a self -\nreinforcing cycle of deterioration.\n\n--- Document 3 (expert1ccf.pdf) ---\n5. What is the role of congestion in heart failure pathophysiology and outcomes?  \nSample expert answer:  \nCongestion is the dominant driver of symptoms, hospitalisation, and prognosis in heart \nfailure and often precedes overt declines in cardiac output. Elevated intracardiac filling \npressures lead to pulmonary and systemic venous congestion, impairing organ fu nction \neven in the presence of preserved systolic performance. Importantly, congestion can be \npresent without significant weight gain or peripheral oedema, highlighting the \nlimitations of traditional clinical assessment. Persistent subclinical congestion \npromotes inflammation, renal dysfunction, and myocardial stress, making effective \ndecongestion a central therapeutic objective in both acute and chronic heart failure \nmanagement.\n=== END EXPERT OPINION ===\n\n=== PATIENT OPINION ===\n--- Document 1 (patient1af.pdf) ---\n1. How did you first realise something was wrong with your heart?  \nSample patient answer:  \nI didn’t initially think it was my heart. I noticed sudden episodes where my heart felt like \nit was racing or fluttering irregularly, often out of the blue. Sometimes it felt like it was \nskipping beats, other times like it was pounding very fast. What made  me worry was that